&lt;p&gt;Now its clear that Kirkwood actually is getting a lot more &amp;ldquo;respect&amp;rdquo; from the model, and Pato&amp;rsquo;s stock has fallen a lot. In fact, Arrow McLaren&amp;rsquo;s stock as a whole seems to have fallen, with O&amp;rsquo;Ward and Nolan Siegel&lt;sup id="fnref:3"&gt;&lt;a href="#fn:3" class="footnote-ref" role="doc-noteref"&gt;3&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/sup&gt; towards the bottom of the list, and Christian Lundgaard losing an expected 90 championships despite his solid start to the season.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This brings us back to the discussion of what the model has &amp;ldquo;learned.&amp;rdquo; Four new races represents just 100 data points for the statistical prediction models to learn off of. Some of our data points are set aside as test data, meaning we are actually closer to 80 new data points since the start of the season. In reality, that&amp;rsquo;s not a lot of new data to really sway the model vs the entire DW12 chassis era.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The simulation piece of this model is more sensitive to this new data, however, as it is taking into account the results from those first 4 races in each of its 10,000 iterations. This means that whatever actually happened in those 4 races is going to move the predictions a lot compared to what the model &lt;em&gt;expected&lt;/em&gt; would happen in those first 4 races.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So why has Pato O&amp;rsquo;Ward lost basically 1300 simulated championships (out of 10,000) to Palou in the last month? The model might be knocking Pato and especially the McLarens down slightly, but Pato has underperformed his expectations in those first four races while Palou has slightly overperformed&lt;sup id="fnref:4"&gt;&lt;a href="#fn:4" class="footnote-ref" role="doc-noteref"&gt;4&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/sup&gt;. Clearly, the 25% of championships that the original model had Pato winning required a lot of good luck in Pato&amp;rsquo;s favor and bad luck in Palou&amp;rsquo;s favor. So far that hasn&amp;rsquo;t happened, and now Pato needs even more luck to not just score more points than Palou, but to make up 50 points in the standings — all in four fewer races than we had to work with at the start of the season.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;To put things another way, the model hasn&amp;rsquo;t changed its mind about O&amp;rsquo;Ward&amp;rsquo;s talent or Palou&amp;rsquo;s talent, or even the quality of their respective cars. But Pato O&amp;rsquo;Ward now needs a lot more luck in his favor on a per-race basis to win the championship, and so the odds of that happening are now much lower.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id="conclusion"&gt;Conclusion:
&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;So is it time to give up on your hopes of a competitive season where someone besides the World&amp;rsquo;s Happiest Spaniard&lt;sup id="fnref:5"&gt;&lt;a href="#fn:5" class="footnote-ref" role="doc-noteref"&gt;5&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/sup&gt; wins a championship? Well, yes and no. 81% is a high probability, but a model like this is a lot slower to learn from more recent data. You and I&lt;sup id="fnref:6"&gt;&lt;a href="#fn:6" class="footnote-ref" role="doc-noteref"&gt;6&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/sup&gt;, on the other hand, tend to react very strongly to recent data. The truth is probably closer to the model&amp;rsquo;s view than the human view, but it&amp;rsquo;s almost certainly somewhere in the middle. So if the rest of the season does follow the human view more than the model&amp;rsquo;s view, we might actually have a fight on our hands between Palou and Kirkwood or Lundgaard.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;And what if the computers are right? Well, it might be a pretty boring season again for those who aren&amp;rsquo;t in the &lt;em&gt;Witness Greatness&lt;/em&gt; camp. If that&amp;rsquo;s the case, however, we can all just start taunting Max Verstappen that he won&amp;rsquo;t quit F1 and come to IndyCar because he&amp;rsquo;s too scared of Alex Palou. At least then there&amp;rsquo;d be hope for a more competitive 2027 season.&lt;sup id="fnref:7"&gt;&lt;a href="#fn:7" class="footnote-ref" role="doc-noteref"&gt;7&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
